<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Govt Makes efforts to Rehabilitate Drug Addicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government is
taking active steps to rehabilitate tens of thousands of drug
addicts in the country.
</P>
<P>
Government hospitals, private medical practitioners, NGO's
centers are providing treatment to drug addicts, according to the
Associated Press of Pakistan (APP).
</P>
<P>
APP quoted official sources as saying these centers have been
successfully engaged in fight against addiction and have cured
more than 0.2 million drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
Detoxification centers in cities like Karachi, Hyderabad,
Lahore, Rawalpindi, Gojranwala, Peshawar, Kohat Mardan, Dera
Ismail Khan are playing effective role for the rehabilitation of
drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
On one hand different government agencies including the Anti-
Narcotics Force, Custom, Police, Rangers are making great efforts
to check drug smuggling and its distribution, on the other hand
the government is engaged in the treatment of the addicts.
</P>
<P>
Prevention through education and awareness is top priority of
the government, which the government hopes to yield good results
to save the future generation from this menace.
</P>
<P>
A program under Drug Abuse Prevention Resources Center has
focused on education on young people including students, women
about the deleterious effects of drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said in order to eradicate drug problem the
Pakistan government has been working to eliminate drug production
by getting rid of cultivation of narcotic crops, harvesting and
processing of opium and cannabis.
</P>
<P>
According to the informed sources there are about 2.5 million
heroin addicts in Pakistan and among them a large number of
addicts are intravenous users.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that rapid increase of switching over to
intravenous mode of drug use is leading to the spread of HIV/AIDS
in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the National AIDS Program sources there are about
80,000 HIV/AIDS cases in Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
