<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU-ASEAN Cooperation Pact to Cover Laos, Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
proposed to include Laos and Cambodia in a cooperation agreement
signed in 1980 by the European Community (EC) and the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), the European Commission said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Commission, the EU's executive branch, has just adopted
proposals for decisions to conclude protocols extending the EC-
ASEAN Cooperation Agreement to the Lao People's Democratic
Republic and to the Kingdom of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The decisions will be approved by the EU Council of Ministers,
the EU's policy-making body. The Commission said it is expected
that the Council will clear the protocols, so that they can be
signed at the end of this month during the ASEAN Post-Ministerial
Conference in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
These Protocols will allow the two Asian countries to benefit
from the European Community economic cooperation projects and
programs provided under the regional cooperation agreement with
ASEAN, and to strengthen their dialogue with the European
Community, which is now still the part of the EU as an economic
pillar.
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner for External Relations Chris Patten said he
welcomed the conclusion of the concerned negotiations, as a
further sign of the durability of the EU-ASEAN partnership -- one
of the EU's longest-standing relationships.
</P>
<P>
"It is all the more welcome since Laos will, on August 1, take
over the coordination of relations between the EU and ASEAN. I
look forward to attending the EU-ASEAN Ministerial Meeting later
this year in Vientiane, Laos," Patten said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
The extension follows the accession of the two countries to
ASEAN on July 23, 1997 and April 30 of last year, respectively. It
came in response to a request by ASEAN member countries, the EU
executive Commission said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
