<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bio-control Method to Save Date Palm Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The scientists of the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) have developed the world's first environment-
friendly bio-technology to save date palm trees from red weevils.
</P>
<P>
The project was carried out by the Ministry of Agriculture and
Fisheries in cooperation with the Arab Organization for Agriculture
Development (AOAD), the official WAM news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The research on "bio-control of red palm weevil" was conducted
at the Agricultural Research Station at Al Hamraniya in Ras al
Khaimah, said WAM.
</P>
<P>
UAE scientists are now able to resort to three locally-developed
bio-techniques to eradicate the red weevil menace and save millions
of hectares of date palm trees in the Gulf states, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The method can initially cut down and later replace the use of
pesticides which are harmful to public life and the environment.
</P>
<P>
It was developed after two and a half years of research under a
project spearheaded by the AOAD and the Arab League, in
collaboration with the Ministries of Agriculture in the GCC states.
</P>
<P>
The project, which has two main research centers in UAE's Ras Al
Khaimah and in Qatif of Saudi Arabia, was funded by the Jeddah-
based Islamic Development Bank and the International Fund for
Agricultural Development, a U.N. body, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
