<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Congress to Pass Prescription Drug Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday urged Congress to reject election-year maneuvering and
appeals of "reckless special interests" and pass his prescription
drug plan for older Americans.
</P>
<P>
"I call on Congress to reject that approach and the reckless
campaign of special interests and act together in the public
interest," Clinton said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Republicans' alternative as "a plan designed for
those who make the drugs, not for the seniors who need to take
them," Clinton said the effort to pass a prescription-benefit
plan has bogged down in Congress because of a "shameless, scorched-
earth campaign."
</P>
<P>
He said that the drug industry has spent 236 million dollars on
its lobbying efforts.
</P>
<P>
"We need a prescription drug benefit that works for seniors and
people with disabilities, not just for the pharmaceutical industry,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Prescription drug is likely to be a priority for older voters
in this year's elections. Clinton hopes to establish a standard,
government-run Medicare benefit while the Republican lawmakers
push for extending drug coverage through government-subsidized
policies.  
</P>
