<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Customer Service Costs U.S. E-Tailers Big Bucks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 8 (Xinhua) -- American Internet retailers
lost about 6.1 billion U.S. dollars in online sales last year by
failing to provide sufficient customer service, a new industry
study said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report from global market analysis firm Datamonitor
estimated that for every complete online transaction nearly four
times as many are abandoned because of poor online service, and 7.
8 percent of these abandoned transactions could have been salvaged
and converted to sales.
</P>
<P>
If this trend continues, Datamonitor forecast a cumulative loss
of more than 173 billion dollars in potentially salvageable sales
over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
"The average company could have improved its online sales
figures by almost 35 percent last year if it had provided better
online customer service for potential customers," the report said.
"This will be particularly important for new dot.com companies who
are now realizing that they have to produce a profit, and soon."
</P>
<P>
The study also predicted that revenues from the sale of e-
service software and services will increase by more than 1,100
percent between now and 2004. The market will grow from 162
million dollars at the end of 1999 to 1.95 billion dollars by 2004.
</P>
<P>
According to Datamonitor, the successful U.S. e-service
companies provide solutions that help Web sites supply the right
customer service, at the right time, through the right channels.
One essential part of the e-service mix is e-mail management.
Other components include Web-based self-help, collaborative
browsing, text chat and voice-over Internet protocol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
