<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Not Ready for Zero Tariff Within EAC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government has
said it will continue its protectionism stance against zero import
tariffs as embraced by other East African Community member states
until a time when its economy grows to such a degree that it can
compete fairly with Uganda and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here Saturday with the visiting delegation of 25
East African parliamentarians, Tanzanian Minister for Industries
and Commerce Iddi Simba said Tanzania is still in its infancy as
far as industrial goods are concerned and that it can not stand at
equal footing in business arena with the other two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"We have to protect our economy. We know how lucrative our
market is to the outside world," said the minister, adding: "If
we open the doors just like that, we would still be mere
consumers of outside goods without ourselves selling our goods."
</P>
<P>
Kenya and Uganda parliamentarians had wanted to know why
Tanzania was not heeding to the call of zero import tariffs
within the East African Community.
</P>
<P>
"Allowing the foreign goods to enter the country at will would
be tragedy to our fledgling economy," Simba added.
</P>
<P>
The East African Community Treaty, which was signed by
presidents of the three countries in Tanzania's northern town of
Arusha last November, is aimed at gradually forging the bloc into
a monetary union and later a political federation.
</P>
<P>
The bloc provides for gradual withdrawal of both the internal
and external tariffs by member states within a duration of four
years after the signing.
</P>
<P>
During the four years, in order to develop internal capacity,
Tanzanian officials have said the country will have to improve
the infrastructure, increase workers productivity and also lower
the costs of electricity, water, telephone and transportation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East African Community Treaty Comes into Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The treaty for the
establishment of the new East African Community (EAC) came into
effect on Friday after Tanzania deposited instruments of
ratification with the Community's Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International
Cooperation deposited the instruments to Muthaura in Dar es
Salaam on Friday. Kenya and Uganda have already done so in
Tanzania's northern town of Arusha, where the EAC secretariat is
based.
</P>
<P>
To witness the ceremony were speakers of the Houses of the
three partner states as well as Zanzibar, a semi-autonomous
region of Tanzania, who were in the one-day East African
Cooperation meeting of speakers of the national assemblies, local
press reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The official inauguration of the EAC by the three Heads of
States will be on November 30, said Muthaura.
</P>
<P>
He said that the rules of procedure for the EAC legislative
assembly indicated a further deepening of the East African
integration.
</P>
<P>
With the community's coming into force, said Muthaura, the role
of parliamentarians will be to promote cooperation among the
national assemblies and their link with the Community's
Legislative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
In this regard the Joint Committee of National Assemblies will
also be expected to promote programs for strengthening and
consolidating the partner states' political, economic and social
cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
The old East African Community collapsed in 1977, partly
because of a divergence of economic policies among the three
member countries.
</P>
<P>
The new East African Community Treaty, which was signed by
presidents of the three countries in Arusha last November, is
aimed at gradually forging the block into a monetary union and
later a political federation.
</P>
<P>
The block is expected to have key organs such as legislative
assembly, community court, sector units and the heads of state
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
