<HEADLINE> Egypt's National Carrier to Resume Flights to Libya Next Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's national carrier will resume
flights to Libya on Thursday, more than one year after the air
embargo imposed against Libya in 1992 by the United Nations
Security Council was suspended, a senior official of the company
said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
EgyptAir will have three flights each week from Cairo to Libya,
two to Tripoli and one to the Mediterranean city of Benghazi,
EgyptAir Stations General Manager Samir Imbabi said.
</P>
<P>
The first plane will carry an EgyptAir delegation to discuss
technical issues with the Libyan side, Imbabi added.
</P>
<P>
Libya's first plane in eight years landed at Cairo International
Airport early Saturday, carrying 11 passengers and a delegation of
Libyan civil aviation officials.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Issa, a top official of the Libyan Arab Airlines (LAA),
said upon arrival that LAA will make 12 return flights a week
between the two countries including seven linking Tripoli and
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Two flights will link the Mediterranean cities of Benghazi in
Libya and Alexandria in Egypt in addition to two weekly flights
between Benghazi and Cairo and one between Cairo and Sabha, 600
kilometers south of Tripoli, Issa added.
</P>
<P>
The international air embargo was suspended more than a year ago
following the handover of two Libyans suspected of the 1988 bombing
of a Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270
people.
</P>
<P>
Officials on both sides have said the resumption of regular
flights has been delayed due to technical and commercial reasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
