<HEADLINE> Iran Urges U.S. to Change Hostile Policies Toward Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Saturday called on the United States to change its hostile
policies toward Iran and follow the example of European countries
in developing relations with the Islamic country.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that expansion of relations with European countries
will lead to a revision of the U.S. policies toward Iran," Kharrazi
was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the appeal while speaking to the German daily "
Frankfurter Allgemeine" on the possible effect of President
Mohammad Khatami's upcoming visit to Berlin next week on the long-
strained Iran-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Iran's expanding ties with Germany and other European countries
will enhance awareness in the U.S. that it has no other choice but
to expand ties with Iran, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, however, that without modifying its hostile
policies toward Iran, the U.S. is in fact ostracizing the American
companies from doing business with Tehran through sanctions.
</P>
<P>
On the Iranian-German ties, Kharrazi expressed hope that
President Khatami's visit to Berlin on July 10-12 will herald new
horizons in political, cultural and economic cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran is interested in developing better ties with the European
Union (EU), so naturally it would like to have good relations with
all important EU members, including Germany, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that other EU countries such as France and Italy were
ahead of Germany in expanding ties with Iran, so Berlin would take
steps to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
On a German court ruling in 1997 that led to tension between the
two traditionally close trade partners, Kharrazi said Iran and
Germany should look to the future in developing their relations and
not be tied to the past.
</P>
<P>
The ruling accused the Iranian government of involvement in the
1992 assassination of Iranian dissidents in a Berlin restaurant.
Iran, in retaliation, arrested a German businessman in Tehran who
was accused of having illegal sex relations with an Iranian woman.
</P>
<P>
Khatami visited Italy and France last year, and German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer visited Iran in March to discuss a trip by
Khatami to Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
