<HEADLINE> Lunar Eclipse to be Observed in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The second and last total lunar
eclipse in 2000 will be observed in the United Arab Emirates (UAE),
said an official at the Sharjah Science Museum.
</P>
<P>
The lunar eclipse, which is to occur on July 16, will last one
hour and 47 minutes. This will be the longest total lunar eclipse
in 140 years, Ghada Abdullah Ali, an astronomer at the museum, was
quoted Saturday by the official WAM news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the museum is organizing special shows and lectures for
visitors to the planetarium to commemorate the celestial event.
</P>
<P>
The UAE registered an invisible partial solar eclipse on July 1,
he added. 
</P>
