<HEADLINE> Iran Refutes Report on Iraqi Oil Smuggled through Iranian Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Saturday denied a recent
report that Iraq has smuggled oil in violation of the U.N.
sanctions imposed on it through Iran's Kish island in the Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the Kish Free Trade Zone said the report by the
Los Angeles Times was "unfounded allegation" against Iran, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Security officers on the island had intercepted a single tanker
smuggling Iraqi oil on March 29 and referred the matter to the
justice department, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
He said an investigation into the oil smuggling case is still
underway.
</P>
<P>
Kish island officials have provided a videotape and 15 photos of
the tanker which violated Iranian territorial waters, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also complained that rumor mongering is routine
for western media. For example, he said, Kish island has bought two
dolphins for a tourist site on the island and they reported that
Iran has bought the dolphins for spying.
</P>
<P>
He underlined Kish island officials, who are committed to
protecting the island's environment, will never allow Iraqi tankers
to spoil the environment of the tourist island.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, under the U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait, has to sell oil under a U.N. supervision system, but
smugglers tend to ship oil from the country for huge money.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian elite Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC)
claimed to have intercepted 12 oil tankers smuggling oil from Iraq
in April for violating Iranian territorial waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
