<HEADLINE> Egyptian Writer Sentenced to Six-month Suspended Imprisonment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court on Saturday handed
down a six-month suspended imprisonment sentence to Ali Salaheddin
Mohsen, a writer accused of defaming Islam by publishing a book
describing Islam's holy book the Koran as the "holy book of Bedouin
ignorance."
</P>
<P>
Mohsen, 43, was found guilty of using his book to spread
extremist ideas with the aim of scorning and disdaining Islam,
Judge Hosam al-Diab told the Giza state security misdemeanors
court, the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The trial began on June 17 after Mohsen was arrested in March at
his home in the Sixth of October town near Cairo after he published
the book "The Shivering of the Lights."
</P>
<P>
He has also been accused of insulting the Prophet Mohammed and
blaming Islam for Arab countries' underdevelopment. Police found
several banned publications at his home.
</P>
<P>
Muslims believe the Koran, as revealed to Mohammed, is the
direct and unalterable word of God. 
</P>
