<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Police Intensify Anti-Drug Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish anti-drug forces have
launched "determined and successful" struggle against illicit drugs
trafficking at three major drug routes through the country, said
Turkish police authorities in a written statement issued on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued amid some newspapers' accusations that
the police failed to conduct efficient anti-drug operations,
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the Directorate General of Security summed up
its latest operations and dismissed the reports as "unrealistic and
baseless," Anatolia said.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, a total of 6,121 people involved in drug trafficking
were arrested in 2,587 separate operations, while anti-drug forces
seized 2,249 kilograms of heroin, 5,458 kilograms of hashish, 288
kilograms of base morphine, 13 kilograms of cocaine, 26.2 tons of
acid anhydride and 1,749,305 captogan pills, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the forces have captured 3,219 suspects in 1,
458 operations, and snatched 2,850 kilograms of heroin, 22.6 tons
of hashish, 976 kilograms of base morphine, 56 kilograms of opium,
6 kilograms of cocaine, 5.5 tons of acid anhydride, 618,336
captogan pills and 14,964 synthetic drugs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 1,583 kilograms of heroin, 50 kilograms of cocaine,
15.5 kilograms of opium and 8.3 tons of acid anhydride were
confiscated in joint operations with the U.S., German, British,
Romanian, Belgian, Russian, Dutch, Spanish, Italian and Greek anti-
narcotics units, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a commercial and cultural bridge between Europe and
Asia because of its geographical position. Nearly 70 percent of
illicit drugs produced in the rest of the world is smuggled to
European countries via Turkey, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has launched global cooperations and forceful struggle
against illicit drugs trafficking in three fronts via the country,
the northern Black Sea route, Balkan route and eastern
Mediterranean route, it said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's efforts and determination to fight drug trafficking
have been praised by the European Union, the U.S. and the United
Nations, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. held a seminar on anti-drug trafficking and organized
crimes in Ankara last month, showing their confidence in Turkish
anti-narcotics forces, it added.
</P>
<P>
The police authorities acknowledged that "there were some
security officials and other officials collaborating with criminal
organizations. But they were arrested and punished."
</P>
<P>
The statement said, however, that some claims overstated the
presence of officials committing crimes, "created a negative image
for Turkey in the international platform" and damaged "our struggle
against drug smuggling." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0038 </DOCNO>
