<HEADLINE> U.N. Deploys Military Observers in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has deployed
military observers in most of the government controlled and rebel
areas in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), a Zimbabwe
National Army (ZNA) official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Acting Spokesman Charles Mugari said in a statement that the
withdrawal of Zimbabwean, Namibian and Angolan troops from the
DRC which supported the DRC government troops to fight the rebels
backed by the Ugandan and Rwandan troops was now imminent
following the U.N. move.
</P>
<P>
Mugari said that "efforts by the United Nations Observer
Mission to Congo have started to gain ground. In Kisangani,
Rwandan and Ugandan troops have completely withdrawn 70 or 30
kilometers respectively."
</P>
<P>
He said the ZNA commander Constantine Chiwengwa was on a tour
of the DRC to brief the allied troops on the ceasefire and the
deployment of the U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
He said Chiwengwa would visit the western, northern and eastern
parts of the DRC where Zimbabwean, Namibian and Angolan troops
were operating.
</P>
<P>
The three countries mounted a defence of the DRC capital
Kinshasa in mid- 1998 against rebels which fought to topple the
Laurent Kabila government.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. promised to send at least 5,500 peacekeepers to
compliment the Lusaka ceasefire agreement signed by all the
belligerents in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been criticized for sending such a few
peacekeepers to the vast country and also for taking long to
deploy them.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola have pledged to remove their
troops from the DRC once the U.N. peacekeepers were in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
