<HEADLINE> World Bank Offers Loan to Africa to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced on
Saturday it had set aside 500 million U.S. dollars for anti-AIDS
programs in African countries.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came on the eve of the 13th International
AIDS Conference in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Vice president of the bank's Africa region, Callisto Madavo,
said the money would come from the bank's soft loan window, the
International Development Association, to fund HIV/AIDS programs
on standard terms of 40 years maturity including 10 years grace.
</P>
<P>
"All that is needed is a sound national AIDS strategy developed
in a participatory way backed by serious government commitment," a
World Bank statement from Washington said.
</P>
<P>
Madavo stressed AIDS was not only a health problem but also a
development one, but "only where governments show leadership can
international support be effective". 
</P>
