<HEADLINE> Intensified Efforts Urged to Fight AIDS in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zuma was speaking while unveiling a giant, red,
three-dimensional AIDS ribbon in Durban in memory of those South
Africans who had died of the disease.
</P>
<P>
The memorial was unveiled ahead of Sunday's start of the 13th
International AIDS Conference in Durban.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said he wanted the memorial to be a symbol of the struggle
of the many South Africans that had and still continued to fight
the disease.
</P>
<P>
"I would like it to serve as a source of courage and
inspiration to all those who live with the disease, to those who
share their homes and lives with victims.
</P>
<P>
"Let their memory in the form of this symbol serve as a
reminder to us at all times that these are not normal times..,"
Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 4.2 million South Africans suffer from
HIV/AIDS while there are 1,700 new infections a day.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said it was in the power of all South Africans to reverse
the rampant path of the HIV/AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
"We need to see more South Africans take up the battle cry in
large numbers to avert the threat of disaster that faces us," Zuma
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the best news that will come out of the conference, as
far as he was concerned, is that an AIDS vaccine will go on trial
soon in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine, a partnership between Britain and Kenya, will go
on trial in the next few months. It would be the first vaccine
aimed at the African HIV strains.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said this news would give hope to those living with the
disease. 
