<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Supports UN Sanctions on Sierra Leone Diamonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhang Dacheng
</P>
<P>
LOME, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim said here Saturday that
the regional body supports sanctions imposed by the United Nations
on Sierra Leone diamonds exports.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua, during a break of the plenary session of the
72nd ordinary session of the OAU council of ministers, that it was
very import for African countries to be in the forefront to fight
against the utilization of diamonds for the perpetration of civil
wars.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously when the (UN) Security Council takes this decision
of that nature, the members of the organization have clear
responsibility to comply with that," he added.
</P>
<P>
The UN Security Council Wednesday voted 14-0 in a resolution to
impose a ban on the diamonds from Sierra Leone, where a thriving
illegal diamond trade is fanning the civil conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council decides that all States shall take the
necessary measures to prohibit the direct or indirect import of
all rough diamonds from Sierra Leone to their territory," the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
Salim also urged Liberian President Charles Taylor to help OAU
in winning the release of all the UN peacekeepers held by Sierra
Leone armed rebels.
</P>
<P>
"We think we should try to make it a task less difficult by
trying to encourage them to go on that purpose so that
peacekeepers are released," he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about Angola which boycotts the forthcoming 36th OAU
summit to be opened here on Monday, Salim said that the UN
sanctions on the Angolan rebels was important to reach
reconciliation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
"I can understand that the Angolans are concerned about the
violation of sanctions, but my view has always been that the
question of sanctions is important for all the African countries,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Namibia and Cape Verde have threatened to boycott the
Lome summit on account of alleged violation by the Togolese
government of the UN sanctions against the rebel National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) led by Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Salim expected the international community to implement the
sanctions against UNITA with the African states in the forefront.
</P>
<P>
"Though Angolan government is not here, the discussion on
Angola was very constructive, and literally there was a total
commitment of the African countries to do their utmost to
implement sanctions," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
The African ministers are in a three-day session to make
preparations for the summit which is expected to discuss mainly on
the three themes of regional cooperation and integration, security
and stability, and the challenges of widespread AIDS and poverty
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
African leaders will also discuss the draft treaty on the
establishment of the African Union initiated during an
extraordinary summit on September 9, 1999, in Syrte, Libya as well
as the treaty on the African Economic Community.
</P>
<P>
Ways to end various conflicts on the continent, particularly in
Angola, Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Sierra
Leone, and the related situation of refugees will also be on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Founded on May 25, 1963, the OAU is designated to promote the
unity and solidarity of the African states, defend the
sovereignty, territorial integrity and independence of members,
and intensify the cooperation and efforts to achieve a better life
for the people of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Following eradicating all forms of colonialism from Africa, the
 organization has been focused on peace and development in the new
millennium and reversion of the growing marginalization of Africa
in economic globalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
