<HEADLINE> IMF Supports Debt Relief for Developing Countries: Kohler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund was in favor of bolder debt relief and the restructuring of
developing countries' voting powers within the organization,
visiting IMF managing director Horst Kohler has said.
</P>
<P>
The South African Press Association Saturday quoted Kohler as
saying that he had discussed the issue with South African
President Thabo Mbeki in Pretoria earlier.
</P>
<P>
"President Mbeki has told me that he would like to see the
speeding up of that process, and I agreed and told him that I
will take the matter to the IMF," he said.
</P>
<P>
But, Kohler warned that his duty would only be to recommend
since the decision to cancel the debt would only come from "those
who were being owed" .
</P>
<P>
He said developing countries needed to work harder to get
credibility and demonstrate they were building economies based on
legitimate democratic structures, free of corruption and
maladministration.
</P>
<P>
Kohler's visit was the last leg of his African tour which
included Nigeria, Senegal, Botswana and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF was in the process of reforming itself and that
 he was trying to listen to everyone, particularly the African
nations.
</P>
<P>
Kohler explained that despite holding the post for only two
months, he had taken the tour of developing countries to get a
first hand experience. 
</P>
