<HEADLINE> Iran Lashes out at U.S. for Stance over Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRNA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Hamid Reza Asefi has strongly lashed out at the United States for
its stance against Iran's verdicts on 10 Iranian Jews on charge of
spying for Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The government of the Islamic Republic of Iran does not allow
any foreign country to interfere in Iran's internal affairs," Asefi
said on Friday evening, quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said the Iranian judiciary is entitled to deal independently
with judicial matters in the country.
</P>
<P>
"How can American officials allow themselves to interfere with
such impudence in the internal affairs of the Islamic Republic of
Iran?" he questioned.
</P>
<P>
Asefi voiced Iran's anger after the U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Wednesday assured U.S. Jewish leaders that he will work to win
the release of the Iranian Jews.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he will try to mobilize leaders in Europe, Russia,
Japan and other countries that have closer ties with Iran to work
together with the U.S. to secure the release of the Jews.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian revolutionary court on July 1 sentenced 10 Jews to
four to 13 years in prison. Two Muslims also received sentences of
two years, while three other Jews and two Muslims were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman said the subsequent statements by U.S.
officials over the spy case indicate the influence of the Zionist
(Israeli) regime on the government in Washington.
</P>
<P>
He called on the U.S. officials not to come under the influence
of the Israeli regime and stop repeating unlawful and illogical
statements about the spy case. 
</P>
