<HEADLINE> Two Suspects Nabbed in Canada's Largest Ecstasy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Canadian police have busted one of
the largest Ecstasy labs and arrested two suspects in Markham,
Toronto, the Toronto Sun newspaper said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
After a month-long probe, police moved in Friday on the lab
nestled in a two-story house, where they arrested two men aged 20
and 21 and seized an AK-47 assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
Police also evacuated 16 Markham homes, fearing an explosion or
toxic spill of chemicals used to make the so-called "love drug".
</P>
<P>
"There's a whole bunch of chemicals in there from sulphuric
acid, acetate, nitrogen gas, nitro-methane, methylene chloride,"
said Const. Michele Paradis.
</P>
<P>
Health Canada chemist John Hugel said similar labs usually have
one or two 20-litre pails of chemicals, but this one had 20 or 30
such containers. 
</P>
