<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 Finance Ministers Agree on Policy Coordination Over IT Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Finance ministers from the Group of
Seven (G-7) major industrialized nations ended their one-day
meeting in Fukuoka, southwestern Japan, Saturday with an agreement
to take a coordinated policy over economic and financial
challenges posed by the information technology (IT) revolution,
Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministers from Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy,
Japan and the United States also made headway on refurbishing the
international financial system by adopting a package of reforms to
International Monetary Fund (IMF) lending mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
On the world economy, the finance chiefs welcomed an
increasingly bright global economic picture.
</P>
<P>
"Prospects for the world economy are good," Japanese Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, who presided over the gathering, said in
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Miyazawa said the ministers agreed on the importance of
carrying out sound financial, macroeconomic and structural
policies to achieve strong and sustainable economic growth over
the medium term.
</P>
<P>
On the IT issue, the G-7 ministers for the first time held in-
depth talks on the IT boom's impact on macroeconomic, financial
and tax policies, with attention on how to maximize the benefits
of the new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
They said in a report that "the advance of the IT revolution
holds the promise of becoming a major force in the global economy
in improving productivity, raising maximum potential output, and
promoting higher living."
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers' meeting will be followed by a meeting of
foreign ministers from the Group of Eight (G-8) major nations --
the G-7 plus Russia -- in Miyazaki on July 12-13 and the summit of
the G-8 leaders in Okinawa on July 21-23.
</P>
<P>
The reports on IT and reform of the global financial system,
will be submitted to G-8 leaders along with two other reports on
global financial crimes and debt relief initiative for poor
countries, which were not made public Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
