<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Jeddah-based Islamic Development Bank(IDB) will
inaugurate the Islamic Corporation for Private Sector Development
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The corporation is aimed at boosting and developing the private
sector in the member states of IDB through promoting and
encouraging the creation of productive projects in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
The number of signatories of the corporation's agreement until
May 23 has reached 30.
</P>
<P>
Among the major tasks to be undertaken by the corporation is the
contribution, whether individually or in collaboration with other
funding resources, in financing the construction works and
expanding and upgrading of the projects.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Treasury announced that 1.2 billion U.S.
dollars in foreign capital investments were permitted in the first
half of 2000, up by 28.1 percent as compared to the same period
last year, reported Turkish Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Permissions were issued for foreign investments mainly in the
service sector, which attracted 78.9 percent of the foreign
capital, followed by the manufacturing industry with 16.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has given permission for 26.75 billion
dollars in foreign investments since 1980.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait's oil revenues are expected to reach about
5 billion dinars (16.5 billion U.S. dollars) during the fiscal year
2000/2001 due to the rising oil prices in the global markets.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti News Agency Friday quoted a weekly report by the "
Shaal Office for Economic Studies" as saying that non-oil revenues
will hit 450 million dinars (1.485 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
On Kuwait's crude oil production, the report said it will reach
about 2.2 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman said it exported the first shipment of 60,000
tons of liquefied natural gas (LNG) to the U.S. on Thursday under a
short-term agreement signed with "Coral Energy" company for gas
marketing, a subsidiary of the "Royal Dutch" group.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Oman will deliver to the U.S. two shipments
of natural gas, whose volume amounts to 260,000 cubic meters in
July and August.
</P>
<P>
Oman is committed to a 25-year contract for selling 4.1 million
tons of LNG annually to Coral Gas company.
</P>
<P>
Oman Gas Company said earlier it will start to export the LNG to
Spain in the last quarter of this year, indicating it has signed
supplying contracts with Japanese and Indian firms. In May, Oman
started the exports of LNG by selling the first shipment to "Total
Vienna Elf" company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
