<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- A project for medicines production, recently approved
by the Bahraini cabinet, is expected to put Bahrain on the top of
the countries making progress in the production of drugs in the
Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
A Saudi daily on Saturday quoted Bahraini Minister of Oil and
Industry Sheikh Isa Al-Khalifa as saying the total investment in
the project is estimated at 50 million U.S. dollars, with an annual
production capacity of about 4,154 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
He stated the project is being carried out by a Swiss company
specialized in drugs and medicines industry. The factory is
expected to produce medicines and drugs used in the treatment of
diseases like cholesterol, cancer, kidney and liver diseases, heart
diseases and neurotic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
He added the new company will export most of its products to the
world markets.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish construction company Ceylan Insaat has sealed
a contract to build 3,500 houses worth 150 million U.S. dollars in
Skopje, Macedonia, reported Turkish Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ceylan Holding CEO Mahmut Ceylan said Friday the company will
start construction of the houses this year and complete the work
within three years.
</P>
<P>
He said talks on other schemes in Macedonia are continuing.
Ceylan has undertaken contracts in Israel, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan
and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Algeria, which consumes about 5 million tons of
grains annually, is expected to see its harvest of grains decline
from 2.2 million tons last year to 1 million tons this season due
to the ongoing severe drought.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of rains had a devastating effect on the areas of
grains planting.
</P>
<P>
The process of harvesting is currently underway and there may be
an increase in the crops, but it is unlikely to exceed 1.2 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Shanghai and Istanbul, the two largest cities of China
and Turkey, are keen to strengthen their economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with visiting Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi on Friday,
Istanbul Mayor Ali Mufit Gurtuna noted that Shanghai, one of the
most important doors of China opening up to the outside world, is
dynamic and continuously developing.
</P>
<P>
Istanbul is Turkey's biggest, most dynamic city and a door
opening to the outside world, Gurtuna stated.
</P>
<P>
He wished relations between Shanghai and Istanbul will continue
to develop.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Xu said he shares the points of view of Mayor
Gurtuna, adding Turkey and China are getting closer by direct
flights that take place twice a week.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his stay in Istanbul, he met with Turkish
businessmen who requested an increase in the number of the flights
and that he shared the ideas with them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
