<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union Urges Protection of Arrested Turkish Cypriot Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Union of Cyprus Journalists
(UCJ) Saturday appealed for the protection of Turkish Cypriot
journalists arrested Friday by the Turkish Cypriot regime in the
northern island.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made to U.N. Secretary-General's Special
Representative in Cyprus, the ambassadors of the permanent members
of the U.N. Security Council and international media organizations.
</P>
<P>
In the appeal, the UCJ reported the arrest and disappearance
Friday night of Editor-in-Chief of Turkish Cypriot daily "Avrupa"
Sener Levent and two or more of his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
"Avrupa" has been persecuted by the Turkish Cypriot regime
because of its views on the Cyprus issue, said the UCJ.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot regime in May confiscated the daily's
equipment and furnitures, after the daily refused to pay a 290,000-
U.S.-dollar fine for alleged defamation of Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The UCJ said that despite the efforts by the families and the
lawyers of the arrested journalists to find out where they are
held, the Turkish Cypriot authorities refuse to give any
information.
</P>
<P>
"We have strong reasons to fear that the lives of the arrested
Turkish Cypriot journalists are in great danger," the UCJ appeal
said.
</P>
<P>
The UCJ said that the fear is based on the accusations labelled
against them by the Turkish Cypriot "Bayrak" radio, controlled by
Turkish army officers and Denktash's administration, that these
Turkish Cypriot journalists are "a gang of conspirators against the
Turkish army."
</P>
<P>
The UCJ called for urgent and effective actions to protect the
lives of Sener Levent and his colleagues and to ensure their
immediate release.
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island of Cyprus has remained divided
into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities since 1974 when
Turkey invaded and occupied the northern part of the island after a
failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
In 1983 the Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally a breakaway
republic, which is only recognized by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
