<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Appeals to Increase Food Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Agricultural
Organization (FAO) has warned that the world has to increase food
production in the next 50 years if hunger is to be eradicated.
</P>
<P>
In a statement obtained here on Saturday, the FAO said that as
the world population increases from the present 6 billion to 8.9
billion, food production should also be boosted.
</P>
<P>
Growing enough food will not lead to the eradication of hunger
unless measures are put in place to make sure that the food gets
into the hands and mouths of the people who lack it, the FAO
said.
</P>
<P>
These measures should involve increasing rural incomes and
access to food by improving agriculture and rural economy, it
added.
</P>
<P>
It observed that 20 percent of people in the developing
countries today survive on diets that do not provide the basic
energy that they need to be active and productive.
</P>
<P>
According to the FAO, hunger and micro-nutrients and
deficiencies have decreased children's learning capacity by up to
10 percent and costed developing countries up to 128 billion U.S.
dollars per year in productivity losses.
</P>
<P>
There is need to take advantage of the new technologies which
hold great potential for improving yield and nutritional quality,
FAO said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the agency noted that the risks posed by genetically
modified foods should also be reduced as these could have an
adverse effect on human health.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the World Food Day will be observed
on October 16 under the theme "A millennium Free from Hunger".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
