<HEADLINE> Singapore Begins Construction of Deep Tunnel Sewerage System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Saturday began
construction of the Deep Tunnel Sewerage System (DTSS), a long-
term project which will transform the management of wastewater in
the city state by convey sewage flows to the deep waters of the
Singapore Straits.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ground-breaking ceremony to mark the beginning
of construction of the ever largest sewerage system in Singapore,
Singapore Minister for the Environment and Minister for
Information and the Arts Lee Yock Suan said the ceremony is "a
milestone event in the development of our sanitation system in
Singapore."
</P>
<P>
"To be built at a cost of about 6 billion Singapore dollars (
about 3.5 billion U.S. dollars, it will meet needs of Singapore's
increasing population and expanding economy through the 21st
century," he said.
</P>
<P>
The DTSS will comprises the North Tunnel, the South Tunnel and
a Spur Tunnel linking them as well as two centralized sewerage
treatment works located at the country's southeast and southwest
corners in areas zoned for industrial use.
</P>
<P>
The project is to be built in two phases over the next 15 years
with Phase One scheduled to go into operation in 2008 and Phase
Two slated to be operational in 2015.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
