<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 10 People Killed in Somali Clan Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 people were killed
and more than 16 others wounded when heavy fighting flared up
between rival militiamen in Dharkaynley district of Southwest
Mogadishu, Somalia Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitnesses, the fighting was between militiamen
loyal to Hussein Aidid and a religious group from the Dudubleh
clan based in and around the Dabaqayn mosque of Dharkaynley
district.
</P>
<P>
During the fighting, Aidid's militiamen used anti-aircraft
rockets, heavy machine guns mounted on battle wagons and all kinds
of assault rifles while those of their opponents merely employed
rocket-propelled grenades, automatic assault rifles and hand
grenades.
</P>
<P>
An eyewitness in the area told the reporter that he had seen
the bodies of three men from the Dudubleh clan religious group as
they were pushed back a while in the first round of the fighting.
</P>
<P>
The fighting culminated after the militiamen of Muse Sudi
Yalahow joined the fighting along side the religious group against
arch-rival Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Thunderous noise of recoilless rifles and mortar rounds were
heard in every corner of the city, reminding the people the sad
old days of the fighting between late General Farah Aidid and Ali
Mahdi Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
According to confirmed sources, the joint forces of the
Dudubleh religious group and Yalahow's fighters have managed to
repulse back the advancing militiamen of Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed sources said the militiamen led by Aidid were
forced to retreat back and even loose control of the Galbed police
station and its surrounding areas which they earlier controlled.
</P>
<P>
Even though the dead were mainly combat militiamen, still there
were quite a number of innocent civilians caught in the middle of
the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
A lady selling tea right at the place said that she had seen
the dead bodies of a beggar and a herdsman whom no one could
identify which clan they belonged to.
</P>
<P>
It is not known how many of Aidid's militiamen died in the
fighting, but sources close to his militiamen said that three of
his fighters were killed and more than six others suffered various
gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
The fighting subsided early in the evening Friday night and the
 situation in the area remained calm for a period. However, it
became tense again on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the fighting is not yet stated officially;
however, independent sources confirmed that taxing of the
commercial goods going in or out of Dharkaynley district has been
the main reason behind the squabble which led to the bloody armed
confrontation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Aidid's militiamen erected a roadblock in the street to Medina
district in which they asked the traffic to pay them extortion
money before they proceeded to their destinations, something the
religious group denied.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the fighting in Medina, there had also been several
other skirmishes elsewhere in Mogadishu. Sporadic exchange of fire
continued early in the morning on Saturday in North Mogadishu
between rival militiamen, but no deaths were reported even though
several people were wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Seeks Preferential Trade Agreement With SACU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is negotiating for a
preferential trade agreement with the Southern Africa Customs
Union (SACU) to enable Zambian products to enter the markets of
its member countries.
</P>
<P>
Briefing journalists in a press conference here on Saturday,
Zambian Minister of Commerce, Trade and Industry William
Harrington said Zambia is not seeking to join the SACU which
groups Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia, Swaziland and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is simply negotiating for a preferential trade agreement
with the SACU members at preferential tariffs, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the proposed Zambia-SACU agreement has been on the
negotiating table for five years.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is meant to be an interim measure to allow Zambia
to gain preferential access into SACU and would fall off with the
implementation of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) protocol, since Zambia and all SACU countries are members
of SADC, he said.
</P>
<P>
Selected Zambian products would enjoy preferential access into
SACU through a quota system, the minister said, adding that while
Zambia will not be required to reciprocate with South Africa, it
would have to reciprocate with Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia and
Swaziland on certain products.
</P>
<P>
Non-reciprocity with South Africa was agreed to due to the
recognition of the large trade imbalance between South Africa and
Zambia in the ratio of 28 to one in favor of South Africa, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Harrington, the trade and industry ministers of
Zambia and the SACU countries meeting in July 1998 in Pretoria,
South Africa had endorsed the agreement in principal, although
there are still a few outstanding issues which have to be resolved
at a bilateral level between Zambia, Lesotho, Namibia and
Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
He said on his way from signing the Cotonou Agreement in Benin
last month, he met his South African counterpart Alec Erwin.
</P>
<P>
"Both my counterpart and I agreed that it would be important to
 concentrate on the SADC trade protocol which is only about two
months a way from implementation," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Pledges 30 Million U.S. Dollars to Help Malawi Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States has pledged to
support Malawi's fight against the scourge of HIV/AIDS with 30
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here on Saturday quoted Ellen Shippy, U.S.
ambassador to Malawi, as saying that the assistance is in line
with U.S. President Bill Clinton's 1999 LIFE initiative, which
singles out HIV/AIDS support to 15 developing countries around the
world. "The United States will continue to support efforts in
Malawi to prevent new infections and those already infected,"
Shippy said.
</P>
<P>
The LIFE initiative came fast on the heel of another pledge by
the United Nations agencies and donors who, three months ago,
vowed to set aside 110 million dollars to assist Malawi's
five-year HIV/AIDS strategic plan.
</P>
<P>
AIDS has wiped out most socio-economic gains Malawi has
achieved since independence from Britain 36 years ago, the World
Bank said.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the life expectancy in the country has fallen
from 47 years in the mid-1980s to 36 years nowadays largely due to
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The average per capita income for Malawi's 10 million people
has also been slashed from 220 dollars to less than 200 dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the National AIDS Control Program, at least 14
percent of Malawi's population is carrying HIV and the killer
disease has already claimed over 360,000 lives and created over a
million orphans since the first AIDS case was diagnosed in the
country in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Stresses Independent Foreign Policy, Toughens Stand on Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
vowed here Saturday to carry out an omnidirectional and
independent foreign policy and to pursue the anti-terrorist
operation in Chechnya to "a perfect end."
</P>
<P>
"Russia is and will be pursuing an independent foreign policy,
which is based on the principles of pragmatism and efficiency and
gives priority to national interests," Putin said in his first
state-of-nation address to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia has encountered a new type of foreign
aggression -- international terrorism -- and, in fact, "a
challenge to its sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Russia's campaign against international
terrorism quite often draws a negative response abroad, Putin said,
adding that it is the priority of its foreign policy tasks to
explain Russia's counter-terrorism efforts.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the anti-terrorist operation in Chechnya
helped to avert the threat of Russia's break-up.
</P>
<P>
The territory of Chechnya has actually become a beachhead for
international terrorist forces whose actions have threatened
Russia's unity in the past few years, and only anti-terrorist
operations can make Russia preserve territorial integrity, the
president stressed.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the important role of the federal military in
solving this problem, pledging to push forward the anti-terrorist
campaign to a full success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
