<HEADLINE> Iraq to Hold Medical Exhibition to Promote Health Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Medical companies from Arab,
European and other countries will hold an exhibition in the Iraqi
capital Baghdad this week, an official said here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Omar Al-Kubaisi, director of the Saddam Health Center, said the
exhibition will group companies from Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Qatar,
the United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, Turkey, France, Italy,
Spain, Portugal, Germany, Indonesia and other countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been intensifying efforts to alleviate the devastating
impacts of the decade-old United Nations sanctions.
</P>
<P>
To hold such exhibitions or products fairs have enabled Iraq to
sign contracts with foreign countries to import medicine, food and
other humanitarian supplies under the U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. humanitarian deal, in place since late 1996, allows
Iraq to sell limited amount of oil to help offset the stringent U.
N. sanctions, which Iraq said have caused a humanitarian crisis in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad said as many as 1.3 million people, mostly children
under five and the elderly, have died as a direct result of the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In a report, the International Committee of the Red Cross has
warned that Iraq's health system is close to collapse and
threatening the very survival of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The situation of the civilian population is increasingly
desperate, the Red Cross said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
