<HEADLINE> Prosecution Closes Evidence in Copter Case Against Pakistani Former PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deputy Prosecutor General of Pakistan Raja Muhammad Bashir said
the prosecution has given up certain witnesses and if defense
wanted to summon them the prosecution will produce them for cross
examination.
</P>
<P>
In total 15 witnesses deposed for the prosecution in the
helicopter case where Nawaz Sharif has been charged of evading
taxes as he had not declared the helicopter in his tax returns
which he owned. On conclusion of the evidence of prosecution, the
court, located in the proximity of Islamabad, asked Nawaz Sharif
when he would want to record his statement.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said he would decide about giving statement before the
court after consulting his lawyers.
</P>
