<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Inflation up in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The prolonged drought and the
increase in value added tax (VAT) has pushed the country's
inflation up, the Central Bank of Kenya has said.
</P>
<P>
According to its latest monthly economic review, the bank
announced the inflation increase to 8.3 percent in June from 8.2
percent in May, the East African Standard newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the increase in inflation to the depression
of the Kenyan shilling, the price hike in fuels, the shortfall in
supply of food and the cost of goods and services caused by the
raise in VAT.
</P>
<P>
Fuel and power, entertainment and education baskets experienced
the highest inflation rates of 14.3 percent and 15.4 percent
respectively, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
While the inflation in the food basket, which has the highest
weight in the consumer price index, reached 4.5 percent in June as
against 3.1 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The bank predicts that this upward inflationary trend is
expected to continue in the short-term due to the prolonged
drought and the shilling's depreciation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
