<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Attach Importance to Ethical Issues in Genome Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists and experts here
today called on the whole of society to pay attention to ethical
issues in human genome research and try to avoid negative effects
of the research.
</P>
<P>
Human society is not fully prepared in the aspects of
psychology, ethics, law and international relations for the rapid
development of the Human Genome Project (HGP), which will bring
new risks and challenges to mankind, said Yang Huanming, a leading
scientist of the HGP in China.
</P>
<P>
He told a forum held by the China Science, Technology and Law
Association that the key problem of the ethics of human genome
study is to build more harmonious social relations and relations
between mankind and nature, based on the new understanding of such
relations.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization, the application of the results of the HGP
and other genetic techniques should not bring hazards to patients,
people who receive tests, and other relevant persons, but should
benefit the health of all.
</P>
<P>
Things which can be achieved by biological technology are not
necessarily compatible with human ethics, said Qiu Renzong, an
expert from the Committee of Social, Ethical and Legal Problems of
the Human Genome Project in China.
</P>
<P>
Qiu also disagreed with the concept that all diseases and human
behavior are decided by genes. He said that some diseases are
caused by social and environmental factors, and a person should be
responsible for his or her behavior instead of blaming genes for
everything.
</P>
<P>
He said that human genome technology should not be used in "
eugenics", which can easily cause inequality among human beings.
</P>
<P>
All the scientists and experts who attended the forum agreed
that the ethical issue in human genome study needs fuller
discussion, so that the research will be guided to develop in the
right way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, Shijiazhuang, Changsha,
Lanzhou and Urumqi reported slightly polluted air today.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center today, fairly good air was
reported in 31 cities. They are Tianjin, Taiyuan, Hohhot, Shenyang,
Dalian, Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong,
Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Hefei, Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai,
Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou, Zhanjiang,
Chongqing, Chengdu, Guiyang, Kunming, Xi'an and Xining.
</P>
<P>
All the 36 aforementioned cities, except Changsha, Shenzhen,
Chongqing, Guiyang and Kunming listed particulates less than 10
microns in size as their major pollutants, while sulfur dioxide is
the major air pollutants in Changsha, Shenzhen, Chongqing, Guiyang
and Kunming.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou, Xiamen, Nanning, Haikou, Lhasa and Yinchuan reported
excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution indexes below 50),
level-two or fairly good (pollution indexes ranging from 51 to 100)
, level-three or slightly polluted (pollution indexes ranging from
101-200), level-four or poor (pollution indexes ranging from 201
to 300) and level-five or hazardous (pollution indexes over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in economically developed coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
