<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Project Set to Explore New Strategies for New Delta Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and neighboring Pearl
River Delta region should maximize their advantages and develop as
partners rather than competitors, a seminar on building a
competitive Pearl River Delta region here was told Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and the Delta region should explore new strategies
that enable them to leverage a total package of each other's
advantages, said Victor Fung when delivering a keynote speech at
the seminar, which was jointly organized the Center of Urban
Planning and Environment Management, the University of Hong Kong
and Hong Kong Institute of Planners.
</P>
<P>
Fung is spearheading a private-sector initiative entitled "
Project 2022" aiming to foster greater understanding of existing
and potential linkage between Hong Kong and the delta, especially
in areas such as the environment, transportation and planning.
</P>
<P>
The project, sponsored by a group of Hong Kong business people
and thus entitled to mark the half-way point for Hong Kong's
mandated 50 years as a special administrative region, explores
specific ways of cooperation and coordination to improve
competitiveness for the delta region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 participants from government, private sector, NGO and
academics in Hong Kong, China's mainland and overseas gathered to
discuss the environment, sustainable development, infrastructure,
cross-border planning, trade, commerce and science and technology
development that are vital to the development of the region.
</P>
<P>
Participants believed that after two remarkable decades of
partnership and growth, Hong Kong and the delta region stand at a
new threshold of opportunity, and three positive trends, namely
China's impending entry into the WTO, Asia's economic recovery and
the Internet revolution, are taking root simultaneously in Asia.
</P>
<P>
They said that these developments herald vastly expanding
possibilities for economic cooperation between Hong Kong and the
delta on many levels and across many sectors, including the "new
economy."
</P>
<P>
Experts involved in the project are also urged to think of Hong
Kong and the delta not as two economic areas each pursuing their
own agenda but as one economic region with a holistic vision of
its future.
</P>
<P>
Dong Hong, director of the development research center of
Guangdong Province, said that the province's development has to
rely on the support of Hong Kong and Hong Kong's prosperity and
stability also have to rely on the province's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The synergy of the two in resources, capital, technology and
manpower will make the region to be the most dynamic and
competitive economic region in the Asia-Pacific region and the
world," Dong noted.
</P>
<P>
Largely on the strength of economic collaboration with the
delta in the past 22 years, Hong Kong rose from the 23rd to 10th
place in the world trading entities from 1978 to 1999 with the per
capita GDP soaring 10 fold to 180,000 Hong Kong dollars (23,000 U.
S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The delta region, meanwhile, has become one of the mainland's
wealthiest, with annual per capita disposable income in Guangdong
reaching 9,000 yuan (about 1,100 U.S. dollars), some 55 percent
more than the national average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
