<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Seaweed Industry Loses 23mln U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' seaweed industry
lost more than one billion pesos (about 23 million U.S. dollars)
in trade opportunities during the past three years, according to a
report of the Philippine News Agency Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The losses were blamed on the poor quality seaweeds supplied by
growers and traders from the central and southern regions of
Visayas and Mindanao, traditional sources of Euchema seaweeds.
</P>
<P>
The seaweeds are used as raw materials in the production of
export-quality carrageenan, a powdery substance used as a gelling
agent in thousands of processed foods, cosmetics, etc. in the
world's markets.
</P>
<P>
The report said the quality of seaweeds had been deteriorating
over the past three years due mainly to the high moisture content
of dried seaweeds being supplied by Visayas and Mindanao traders
and growers.
</P>
<P>
"There seems to be deliberate adulteration of seaweeds with
salt and lime to make them look dry and heavier even when they're
still wet," Benson Dakay, president of the Seaweed Industry
Association of the Philippines, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
With seemingly "heavier and dryer" seaweeds, some of these
suppliers were getting much bigger revenues than they deserved
since they are all paid by the weight, he said.
</P>
<P>
Seaweed processors had been suffering from lower yields for
every metric ton of dried seaweeds they bought from suppliers in
the South, he said, adding that yields for every metric ton they
bought had fallen from 28-20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is presently the world's largest supplier of
seaweeds and producer of carrageenan, controlling a major share of
the 300 million-U.S.-dollar global markets covering America,
Europe and Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Still to Seek Special Powers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
made it clear Saturday that he will pursue his intention to seek
extraordinary, but limited, economic powers to speed up
rehabilitation efforts in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement that he will proceed with the
implementation of development projects in the once-neglected
southern island, "with or without these powers."
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to some reports published today, I would like to make
it clear that I am not backing down in my intention to seek
extraordinary powers from Congress to fast-track rehabilitation
efforts and the implementation of development projects in Mindanao,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said the president appeared to retreat from
seeking special emergency powers to rehabilitate Mindanao in face
of strong opposition from the Congress.
</P>
<P>
He reportedly told Palace reporters on Friday that "if they don
't want it, I don't want it either. It's not that important to me,
" alluding to a proposed Mindanao Crisis Act of 2000 granting
emergency powers to the government.
</P>
<P>
Several senators and congressmen argued that there was no need
for emergency powers as the president could use the powers already
available to him.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said in the statement that his "determination to
transform Mindanao into the country's next food basket and uplift
the lives of its people remain strong."
</P>
<P>
"As I have said, nobody can stop me from giving my full
attention to the development of Mindanao," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also stressed that projects covered by the proposed
special powers measure now being studied by the government would
undergo public bidding through the electronic billboard system,
which will help promote transparency and eliminate graft in the
award of contracts for the projects.
</P>
<P>
"I would also like to stress that proposed special powers
measure now under study by Malacanang (the Presidential Palace)
will rule out negotiated contracts for projects in Mindanao," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I have already stated that the government will still conduct
public biddings as part of the process in the awarding of these
projects. But in order to speed up their implementation, we will
push for the adoption of the electronic billboard system in the
public bidding of these projects. This state-of-the art system
will ensure that government transactions involving Mindanao
projects remain transparent and graft-free," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
