<HEADLINE> India's Foreign Exchange Reserves Recover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- India' foreign exchange reserves,
which had witnessed a 10-week decline, rose by 260 million U.S.
dollars to 36.73 billion dollars during the week ended June 30,
compared to the previous week, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI)
said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The rise in reserves was on account of an increase of 163
million U.S. dollars in foreign currency assets in the reporting
week compared to the previous week, said the RBI in its weekly
statistical supplement.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of foreign currency assets now stands at 33.
774 billion U.S. dollars, said the supplement.
</P>
<P>
India's gold reserves rose by 97 million U.S. dollars to 2.948
billion dollars in the week ended June 30, while the country's
special drawing rights remained static at 8 million U.S. dollars,
it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
