<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Urges Firm State Rule, Free Economy in State of Nation Address </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
made his first state of the nation address to the parliament
Saturday, in which he stressed strong central authority and an
open economy as a cure for the country.
</P>
<P>
"The state power's indecisiveness and weakness bring our
economic and other reforms to nothing. The power must lean on law
and the single executive vertical system," Putin told the Federal
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"A national idea is already ripening in our society. Despite
the variety of political parties in the country, we have always
had common goals which unite us and help us be a single people,"
Putin said, noting that "real federative relations have not yet
been fully built and developed in Russia."
</P>
<P>
"We do not yet have a proper federative state," said the
president, urging all branches of the state authority to "stop
vying for powers" and to "pass over to cooperation in tackling
national problems."
</P>
<P>
On the country's economy, Putin said he regards the state's
inefficiency as the main reason behind the protracted economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"A state's excessive intrusion in spheres where it must not be
and lack of attention where it is necessary" is observed in Russia,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
The president described high taxes, officials' arbitrariness
and an outburst of crime as the main barriers for economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
"The economy's orientation towards raw-material still remains,"
which depends on the state of the market, and "a considerable part
of our economy is still in the shadows," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
The particular problem is the burden of foreign debt, which "
poses a threat to the state. At least a third of the state budget
revenues are spent on "servicing and clearing debts," the
president remarked.
</P>
<P>
The key role of the state in economy consists in protecting
economic freedom. "The essence of state regulation of the economy
is not the state's expansion into different spheres or support for
the chosen ones, but the protection of private initiatives of all
forms of ownership," Putin emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He called for "curbing all attempts to limit economic freedom
in the provinces as unconstitutional." 
</P>
</TEXT>
