<HEADLINE> Cyprus Cooperates With Greece in British Diplomat Murder Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Intelligence (KYP) is helping
Greece hunt for the suspects in the assassination of the British
military attache in Athens last month, local media reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Saunders, 53, military attache of the British embassy to
Greece, was shot dead on June 8 when he was driving to work on a
busy Athens street.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the murder, Greek media published a list of names of
alleged members, some of them Cypriots, of the terrorist group
called November 17 which has claimed responsibility for the
assassination.
</P>
<P>
The Greek secret service requested its Cypriot counterpart that
evidence be collected on the belief that Greek Cypriots belonging
to the elusive November 17 organization could be hiding on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Greek intelligence chief Pavlos Apostolides recently visited the
island looking for clues in the murder investigation.
</P>
<P>
Saunders, who had a local connection as he had previously served
in Cyprus, was the 23rd victim murdered by the November 17
terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
But no one from the November 17 group has ever been caught since
the group started its activities in 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
