<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: International Community More Determined to Contain AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Yu Dabo
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The international community
will beat the drum again to rally more resources to fight HIV/AIDS
which is spreading at an alarming pace in the world, and in the
African continent in particular.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11,500 delegates and dignitaries from across the
world will gather in Durban, a South African coastal city, on July
9-14 to address the HIV/AIDS issue with an ever firmer
determination to contain the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The official opening of the 13th World AIDS Conference at
Kingsmead cricket stadium in Durban on Sunday night will be
watched live in 70 countries across the globe, the organizers
said.
</P>
<P>
But will the conference prove effective in reining in the
rampant spread of AIDS that has already claimed 18.8 million
people since the first AIDS patient was diagnosed in the United
States in 1981?
</P>
<P>
A U.N. report, released days before the conference, revealed
that last year 5.4 million people globally were infected with the
virus bringing the number of those living with the disease to 34.3
million.
</P>
<P>
Africa has the largest number of AIDS sufferers -- 25 million,
with sub- Saharan African region registering the bulk of the
number -- about 24 million. South Africa alone has 4.2 million
sufferers, the largest number in the world.
</P>
<P>
About half of the adult Africans living with HIV are aged
between 15 and 34, at least three-quarters are in the prime of
their economically productive and childbearing life.
</P>
<P>
The disease's ultimate toll on the region is likely to be far
more severe than what is evident today, experts warned.
</P>
<P>
According to South African Deputy President Jacob Zuma, while
it is scientifically accepted that HIV/AIDS knows no social,
gender or racial boundaries, it is a fact that the virus is to be
found in greater concentration among the poorer sections of
society.
</P>
<P>
It is true that AIDS and poverty are synonymous and because of
the disease, poverty is getting worse just as the need for more
resources to curb the spread of HIV and alleviate the epidemic's
impact on development grows.
</P>
<P>
Thus the call for more international aid to alleviate Africa's
poverty is growing stronger.
</P>
<P>
"It's time to make the connection between debt relief and
epidemic relief," the U.N. report said.
</P>
<P>
African governments are paying out four times more in debt
service than they now spend on health and education, the report
said, urging the international community to relieve some of
Africa's external debt so as to allow these countries to reinvest
the savings in poverty alleviation and AIDS prevention and care.
</P>
<P>
"If not, poverty will just continue to fan the flames of the
epidemic," the report warned.
</P>
<P>
UNAIDS, a U.N. anti-AIDS agency, estimated that 1.6 billion to
2.6 billion U.S. dollars would be required to create a "package"
for Africa that would focus on limited use of antiviral drugs to
prevent mother-to- child transmission of the virus, and treatment
of tuberculosis and other infections complicating AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, wealthy countries have become apparently more
concerned with the plight of epidemic-ravaged countries, partly
because the latter may pose threats to global social stability.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, several drug companies have committed
themselves to cutting the price of AIDS drugs in the developing
world.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Vice President Al Gore proposed earlier this year an
increase of 100 million dollars in the U.S. contribution to
anti-AIDS efforts in developing countries to a total of 325
million.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. survey released last month found that two-thirds of
Americans support using federal funds to help address the AIDs
epidemic in Africa, with one-third "strongly" supporting the idea.
</P>
<P>
International assistance is very important for Africa in
fighting AIDS. Meanwhile, some African countries have begun to
find a solution of their own.
</P>
<P>
"Here in our own continent we are seeing we need an African
solution to the problem," Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
Confronted with the great challenge, African countries are
intensifying their campaign and have achieved good results.
</P>
<P>
Senegal managed to intervene early in the course of its HIV
epidemic, maintaining one of the lowest infection rates in
sub-Saharan Africa through effective intervention and emphasis on
prevention. Less than 2 percent of adults are believed to be
infected in the country.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, the disease's prevalence has fallen from 14 percent
to 8 percent thanks to the prevention campaigns and care. In
Lusaka, Zambia, the percentage of pregnant teenagers infected with
HIV has dropped by half in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
In some places, condom use is becoming the norm among sexually
active teenagers and more teenagers are delaying the age of first
intercourse.
</P>
<P>
The anti-AIDS struggle is uphill, but there are reasons for
optimism as demonstrated by the successful examples above.
</P>
<P>
"Our fight must be relentless, and our efforts doubled" to make
the goal of a safe and secure Africa a reality, Zuma said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
