<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Claims Nine Lives in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A week-long intense heat wave has
claimed nine lives across Turkey so far, reported Turkish Daily
News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to meteorology bulletins, Turkey is experiencing its
hottest July in some 60 years.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the week, temperatures have sprung up
rapidly. Average daytime temperatures soared from about 37 degrees
Celsius to 45.6 degrees Celsius Friday. The highest temperature was
registered at 48.5 degrees Celsius in Cizre of Sirnak province,
adjacent to Syria and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Halil Ergen, aged 59, died of an asthma attack as a result of
the high temperature in his hotel room in the southern
Mediterranean city of Antalya.
</P>
<P>
To the east of Antalya, two soldiers trying to cool themselves
down under the scorching sun were drowned while wading into the
Dicle River.
</P>
<P>
In the southeastern province of Batman and the Eskisehir
province in the west of Ankara, six people were found dead
apparently due to the high temperature.
</P>
<P>
The number of people seeking medical help has also sharply
increased. Turkish Heart Foundation Chairman Cetin Yildirim Akin
said that scorching heat and high humidity had heightened the risk
of heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
Animals are also affected by the heat. Camel drivers soaked
their animals in an effort to cool them down after temperatures hit
45 degrees Celsius, while in northwest Turkey 5,200 chickens were
killed by the heat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
