<HEADLINE> Military in Full Offensive Against Moro Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Government troops are now on the
second stage of their offensive to capture the headquarters of the
secessionist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Some 6,000 soldiers have been deployed to take Camp Abubakar,
the last remaining MILF stronghold in the province of Maguindanao
in Mindanao, according to a report of the Philippine news agency
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They are supported by dozens of armored vehicles, Howitzers,
bomber aircraft and attack helicopters, the report added.
</P>
<P>
"We are inching our way to our objective," Capt. Noel Detoyato,
spokesman of the 6th Infantry Division of the Philippine Army, was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Detoyato said government forces seized two more MILF satellite
camps on Friday in the town of Barira in Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
Although it is hard to set a time frame for the capture of Camp
Abubakar, combined Army and Marine forces will try their best to
take the sprawling 10,000-hectare base in a week' time, he said.
</P>
<P>
But Detoyato admitted that it will not be an easy task to
capture Abubukar since MILF rebels have fortified their camp with
concrete bunkers and running trenches.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Air Force light bombers and helicopter gunships
alternately conduct daily airstrikes on rebel positions to soften
the defenses around Camp Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada ordered the military on Friday to
arrest top MILF leaders once Camp Abubakar is overrun.
</P>
<P>
"They (MILF leaders) are the enemy," he said. "They should be
captured because they are challenging the sovereignty of this
country."
</P>
<P>
The military began launching attacks on Camp Abubakar after the
MILF failed to meet a June 30 deadline set by President Estrada to
sign a peace deal with the government and rejected government
demands to abandon its bid for independence and stop terrorist
acts.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has earlier threatened to retaliate if the government
forces continue to attack Camp Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has been fighting for two decades for an independent
Islamic state in Mindanao. Conflicts between government troops and
MILF rebels have reportedly displaced at least 500,000 civilians
since late April when the military launched attacks on rebel
encampments along the Narciso Ramos Highway in Maguindanao.
</P>
</TEXT>
