<HEADLINE> WHO Lauds Uganda's Malaria Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
has praised Uganda for taking the lead in Africa in the fight
against malaria by waiving taxes and tariffs on mosquito nets and
insecticides, the New Vision daily reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
More Ugandans will now be able to afford nets and insecticides,
the " essential tools for protection against the disease that
kills more than 1 million people worldwide every year," said Wash
Teklehaimanot, acting Project Manage of Roll Back Malaria (RBM).
</P>
<P>
"Uganda has set the pace and we need to see other African
nations follow this excellent example," he said.
</P>
<P>
RBM is a global partnership of United Nations agencies,
governments and non-governmental organizations committed to
reduce malaria-caused death toll in the world.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's move is the first following a series of "hard hitting
pledges" made by African presidents at the African Malaria Summit
in Abuja, Nigeria in April this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
At the Abuja summit, African nations developed a plan to
accelerate the fight against malaria and pledged to reduce or
waive taxes and tariffs on all equipment used in malaria control.
</P>
</TEXT>
