<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fails to Hit Target in Anti-Missile Test EDS-Updates with more details </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. interceptor missile
failed to hit a speeding target warhead in space in a 100-million-
U.S.-dollar test of the proposed National Missile Defense (NMD)
system early Saturday, the Defense Department said.
</P>
<P>
"We failed to achieve an intercept," said Pentagon spokesman
Bryan Whitman in a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We did not intercept the warhead. We are disappointed," said
Ronald Kadish, director of the Ballistic Missile Defense
Organization of the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
Kadish said that because the "kill vehicle" did not detach from
the booster, it never activated the on-board sensors and other
high-tech devices that it would use to intercept the warhead.
</P>
<P>
The "kill vehicle" apparently did not separate from the booster
missile because it did not receive a necessary electronic signal,
he said, adding that it might take days for the Defense Department
to understand why the internal booster signal was not received.
</P>
<P>
The failure is an apparent setback in the Pentagon's drive to
develop the NMD.
</P>
<P>
After fixing a last-minute technical glitch that delayed the
start of Saturday's test by about two hours, a modified Minuteman
intercontinental ballistic missile with a dummy warhead atop its
third stage rocket blasted off from Vandenberg Air Force Base,
California State, at 12:19 a.m. EDT (0419 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one minutes later, at 12:40 a.m. EDT (0440 GMT), an
interceptor missile carrying a warhead-blasting "kill vehicle" was
launched from Kwajalein Atoll on the Marshall Islands.
</P>
<P>
The interceptor was supposed to have collided with the mock
warhead after about 10 minutes of flight over the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
This was the third test of the intercept program. The first
such test last October was successful, although there was a
problem with finding the approaching warhead. A second such test
failed early this year.
</P>
<P>
The next attempted test is scheduled for this fall, but that
timetable might now be put back, according to Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
If Saturday's test had succeeded, it could have moved the
United States a step closer to building the NMD which Congress
says is urgently needed, but which critics decry as unworkable.
</P>
<P>
The anti-missile system is designed to provide protection for
all 50 U.S. states against ballistic missile attacks from other
countries.
</P>
<P>
A base with 20 interceptor missiles would be built in Alaska
State, along with a new radar to help guide the missiles to their
target. By 2007, under the current schedule, the system would be
expanded to 100 interceptor missiles. The Pentagon estimates the
cost at 36 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Arms control experts said the U.S. NMD, opposed by the
international community, will not only spark a new arms race, but
also threaten security and stimulate nuclear proliferation,
instead of promoting security and stemming the spread of nuclear
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
