<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Iraqi-Built Oil Refinery to be in Operation Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The first locally-constructed oil
refinery in Iraq, with a capacity of 10,000 barrels a day, is
expected to go into operation in the next few days, the official
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Citing an official at the Ministry of Industry and Minerals, the
INA said the oil refinery is located in Baiji area, some 200
kilometers north of the capital Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The success of building small oil refineries will encourage Iraq
to build big ones to break foreign monopoly in this field, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
The oil refinery is one of the 12 oil refineries, each with a
capacity of 10,000 barrels a day, to be built by joint teams from
the Iraqi Military Industry Commission and the Ministry of Industry
and Minerals.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been making efforts to improve its oil facilities,
which have become dilapidated as a result of the 1991 Gulf War and
the decade-old United Nations sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long accused the United States and British delegates at
the U.N. Sanctions Committee for blocking contracts it signed with
foreign countries to import oil equipment and spare parts.
</P>
<P>
During the fifth, sixth and seventh phase of the U.N. oil-for-
food program, Iraq signed contracts worth 1.5 billion U.S. dollars
with foreign countries to rehabilitate its oil industry, but only
770 million dollars worth of contracts were approved.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to sell limited amount of
oil to buy basic goods in an exemption to the stringent sanctions
imposed on Iraq since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's current production is 3.1 million barrels a day, of which
600,000 barrels are consumed domestically and 2.5 million barrels
are for exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
