<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Farmers Reduce Hectarage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's commercial tobacco
farmers have reduced irrigated tobacco area for the current season
from 32,000 to 28,000 hectares owing to the problems surrounding
the land acquisition program.
</P>
<P>
Kobus Joubert, president of the Zimbabwe Tobacco Association
(ZTA), told the Zimbabwe News Agency on Friday that some 294
tobacco commercial farms, which represent an estimated 12,590
hectares, have been listed for acquisition.
</P>
<P>
He said the continued farm invasions by war veterans and
villagers have seriously reduced business confidence and security
among most tobacco commercial farmers.
</P>
<P>
"The government should move quickly to evict war veterans in
the interest of the tobacco industry and the economy at large,
since the farmers are working on a seasonal time constraint," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Joubert, Zimbabwean tobacco commercial farmers
planted 32, 000 hectares of seedbed last year, but this year they
have only managed to plant about 28,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
"War veterans have disturbed business by causing work stoppages
and land has not been pegged," he said.
</P>
<P>
The former freedom fighters have occupied about 1,500 white
farms since February this year to pressure the government to speed
up land reform.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, the United States and Brazil produce the best tobacco
in the world and tobacco is Zimbabwe's single largest foreign
currency earner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
