<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Treasury Secretary Renews Call on Japan to Spur Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers on Saturday renewed a call for Japan's continued
simulative efforts to fortify its budding economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
In a 45-minute meeting in Fukuoka, southwestern Japan, Summers
told Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa that monetary,
fiscal and structural policies are the key to returning Japan's
economy back to health, the Kyodo News Services reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Summers urged Japan to redouble efforts to
achieve recovery led by expansion of domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
"The achievement of sustained domestic demand-led growth is an
absolute, crucial priority for Japan," he said, "We believe that
it is appropriate that the Japanese government continue to
maintain that priority."
</P>
<P>
His remarks are regarded as urging the Bank of Japan (BOJ) to
maintain its hyper-easy monetary policy as speculation mounts that
the central bank will decide to abandon the policy soon.
</P>
<P>
The BOJ has maintained the policy of guiding the unsecured
money rate to around zero since February last year.
</P>
<P>
Miyazawa did not divulge his own opinion on the BOJ's monetary
policy stance and told Summers that monetary policy is the central
bank's prerogative, Japanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese finance minister explained the state of Japan's
economy in detail, citing a sharp upturn in gross domestic product
in the January-March quarter and weak personal spending.
</P>
<P>
Miyazawa and Summers met just prior to the beginning of a
meeting of finance ministers from the Group of Seven (G-7)
industrial nations in Fukuoka, Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
