<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fails to Hit Target in Anti-Missile Test EDS-Updates with more information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. interceptor missile
failed to hit a speeding target warhead in space in the third test
of the proposed National Missile Defense (NMD) system early
Saturday, the Defense Department said.
</P>
<P>
The failure raised the possibility of a substantial delay in
the Pentagon's timetable of having the NMD system ready for use by
the end of 2005.
</P>
<P>
"We failed to achieve an intercept," said Pentagon spokesman
Bryan Whitman. Details were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
After fixing a last-minute technical glitch that delayed the
start of the test by about two hours, a modified Minuteman
intercontinental ballistic missile with a dummy warhead atop its
third stage rocket blasted off from Vandenberg Air Force Base,
California State, at 12:19 a.m. EDT (0419 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one minutes later, at 12:40 a.m. EDT (0440 GMT), an
interceptor missile carrying a warhead-blasting "kill vehicle" was
launched from Kwajalein Atoll on the Marshall Islands.
</P>
<P>
The interceptor was supposed to have collided with the mock
warhead after about 10 minutes of flight over the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The first such test last October was successful, although there
was a problem with finding the approaching warhead. A second such
test failed early this year.
</P>
<P>
The next attempted test is scheduled for this fall, according
to Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
If Saturday's test had succeeded, it could have moved the
United States a step closer to building the NMD which Congress
says is urgently needed, but which critics decry as unworkable.
</P>
<P>
The anti-missile system is designed to provide protection for
all 50 U.S. states against ballistic missile attacks. A base with
20 interceptor missiles would be built in Alaska State, along with
a new radar to help guide the missiles to their target. By 2007,
under the current schedule, the system would be expanded to 100
interceptor missiles. The Pentagon estimates the cost at 36
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Arms control experts said the U.S. NMD, opposed by the
international community, will not only spark a new arms race, but
also threaten security and stimulate nuclear proliferation,
instead of promoting security and stemming the spread of nuclear
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Says Web Remains Man's World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Internet is still a man's
world in many countries around the globe as far as Web surfers are
concerned, said a new audience report Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although women Web surfers in the United States have achieved
better-than-parity with the men, the demographic split remains
heavily weighted toward males in Australia, Ireland, New Zealand,
Singapore and the United Kingdom, according to U.S. Web
measurement service Nielsen/NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Internet audience is slightly weighted toward females,
who represented 50.8 percent of the activity in May, while males
represented 49.2 percent of the overall audience.
</P>
<P>
The widest gender gap was seen in the UK, where almost 61
percent of the May audience was male. In Singapore, females
accounted for only 44.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to NetRatings, the demographic split in the Internet
audience in the U.S. has evened out over the past 18 months. The
female audience is primarily visiting shopping sites, home sites
or general interest sites. In other countries, female audience are
still searching for sites they can visit and re-visit for
information pertinent to their daily lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
