<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Small Industry Sector Fails to Attract Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's small and cottage
industry sector has miserably failed to achieve its target to
attract investment for the 1999-2000 fiscal year, the Financial
Express reported here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It had neither reached its target to develop entrepreneurship
nor even touched the target for generation of employment and the
setting up of new industrial units in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Small and Cottage Industries Corporation (BSCIC)
set a target for registration of 6,640 new small and cottage
industrial units across the country in the last fiscal year,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
However, it had been able to enlist about 2,897 industrial
units in the first three quarters of the last fiscal year. The
percentage of the achievement is 43 against its stipulated target
of 75 percent during the period.
</P>
<P>
The BSCIC fixed a target to develop about 34,622 entrepreneurs
at small and cottage industry level throughout the country, but it
was able to develop only 19,251 in the last nine months, achieving
merely 56 percent of the target.
</P>
<P>
The BSCIC's poorest performance was in the field of employment
generation. It has employed about 42,051 people during the nine-
month period in small and cottage industry sector against its
annual target of employment set at 172,684 people, attaining a
success of a meager 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Survey of Bangladesh, a publication of the
Ministry of Finance, also presented a gloomy picture of the
country's small and cottage industry sector by revealing that the
sector achieved only four percent growth in the last fiscal year
against 8.3 percent growth in the fiscal year 95-96. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
