<HEADLINE> Thai PM to Meet G-8 Leaders in Japan EDS: Correction in 4th Paragraph </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
will meet key G-8 leaders in Tokyo on July 20, prior to the group'
s summit from July 21 to 23 in the western Japanese city of
Okinawa, Thailand News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Both U. S. President Bill Clinton and Russian President
Vladimir Putin have confirmed they will attend the session, which
is scheduled for the afternoon of July 20 and will be followed by
dinner.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was invited as chair of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations and of the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development.
</P>
<P>
Chuan will join leaders from Nigeria, chair of the Group of 77,
Algeria, chair of the Organization of African Unity, and South
Africa, chair of the Nonaligned Movement, at the Tokyo meeting.
</P>
<P>
Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan was quoted as saying that
the initiative stemmed from the late Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi, who had wanted the voice of developing countries,
especially those in Asia, to be heard at the G-8 talks.
</P>
<P>
"This (brainstorming session) will open the doors for
developing countries to put forward their views since decisions to
be made at the summit will affect them," Surin said, adding that
the Okinawa meeting would set a precedent for the following G-8
summit.
</P>
<P>
Thailand would like to see the G-8 "deliver a clear message"
for the bridging of the digital gap between developing and
developed countries, Surin said.
</P>
<P>
The global challenge posed by technology will be on top of the
agenda at the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
A week before the leaders' gathering in Tokyo on July 12, Surin
and his counterparts from these developing nations will meet the G-
8 foreign ministers in the southern Japanese city of Miyazaki.
</P>
<P>
Besides urging the G-8 leaders to discuss new issues facing
globalization, Surin said he will also urge Asia as a whole to
step up cooperation with Africa through the United Nations.
</P>
