<HEADLINE> Fiji's Coup Supporters Take a Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's coup supporters Saturday
took the town of Korovou in east Fiji's Tai Levu district.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Radio Company, the town's police
station is now controlled by a man giving the false name of Tiko,
who says he is a cousin of Geiorge Speight.
</P>
<P>
He denies the policemen in his care are hostages.
</P>
<P>
The weapons they used to take the police station were taken
from soldiers based in the town.
</P>
<P>
The town is now sealed at each end by road blocks manned by
hooded men who armed with military assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
In the early morning on Saturday, coup leader George Speight
and the military authorities reached an agreement, according to
which, the 27 hostages held in the country's parliament compound
since June 5 would be released on the same day that the Great
Council of Chiefs is convened. 
</P>
