<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Starts Anti-Missile Defense Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States launched a
missile carrying a dummy warhead in a key National Missile Defense
(NMD) system test early Saturday, the Defense Department said.
</P>
<P>
A modified Minuteman intercontinental ballistic missile lifted
off from Vandenberg Air Force Base in California State at 0.18 a.m.
EDT (0418 GMT) and thrust its target payload toward the Marshall
Islands on the Pacific 6,880 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
The missile, which lifted off shortly after midnight, headed
toward the central Pacific, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
Within 20 minutes of liftoff, an interceptor missile carrying a
warhead-blasting "kill vehicle" was to launch from Kwajalein Atoll
on the Marshall Islands in an attempt to track, intercept and
smash into the approaching warhead in space high above the Pacific
Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
