<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Colorado Wildfire 30 Percent Contained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. federal official said
Friday that firefighters had contained 30 percent of a wildfire in
Buster Flats, a remote section of northwest Colorado 30 kilometers
south of the border with Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
The fire had scorched 10,050 acres since being ignited by a
lightning strike Monday, said Lynn Barclay, a member of the
federal interagency management team fighting the fire. She
predicted the fire would be fully contained by Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Ridgetop winds of 55-65 kph in recent days have made fighting
the fire difficult, Barclay said. Three to four tankers have been
dropping retardant on the fire, but the winds have blown the
retardant from its target, lessening its impact.
</P>
<P>
Another obstacle has been the rugged terrain. Many of the 220
firefighters have been ferried to the fire by helicopter, she
added.
</P>
<P>
No one has been hurt. No structures have burned, and none is
threatened, Barclay said.
</P>
<P>
Campers who were evacuated earlier in the week from Lodore
campground on Dinosaur National Monument have been allowed to
return to the camp site, she said.
</P>
<P>
Rafters along the popular Green River, who applied years ago
for their rafting permits, have been allowed to travel on the
water unimpeded, she said.
</P>
<P>
In neighboring Wyoming state, two wildfires had scorched about
22,500 acres of juniper and sagebrush. No structures were
threatened but one firefighter was treated for heat stroke,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The fire season is shaping up as the worst since 1996,
according to the National Interagency Fire Center in Idaho. It
began more than a month ago with blazes engulfing areas of Florida
and the Southwest, most notably in Los Alamos, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
About 44,300 fires covering more than 1.2 million acres have
been recorded nationwide so far, with drought getting worse in the
West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
