<HEADLINE> Vast Wildfires Burn in U.S. Alaska </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 30 wildfires are
burning the outer areas around Fairbanks in Alaska, the state's
second-largest city, according to reports reaching here late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Visibility is down to one mile, where you can't see the hills
nearby or make out the sun," said Toivo Luick, a chemist with the
Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation.
</P>
<P>
The largest fire, according to officials managing the Alaska
wildfires, is the lightning-sparked 153,700-acre Zitziana blaze
burning near Manley, a village 150 kilometers west of Fairbanks.
Its southern flank was halted when it reached the burned-out
remains of a 1976 fire.
</P>
<P>
Large, lightning-ignited wildfires are typical in the summer in
interior Alaska. Summer daylight warms the area nearly around the
clock, and the wildfires are considered part of the normal forest
regeneration cycle.
</P>
<P>
As of Friday, 311 wildfires had burned nearly 584,000 acres in
Alaska this year, the Fire Information Center said.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, the fire season is shaping up as the worst since
1996, according to the National Interagency Fire Center in Idaho.
It began more than a month ago with blazes engulfing areas of
Florida and the Southwest, most notably in Los Alamos, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
About 44,300 fires covering more than 1.2 million acres have
been recorded nationwide so far, with drought getting worse in the
West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
