<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Agency to Train Bangladeshi Experts to Assess Gas Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States Geological Survey (
USGS) will train six or seven Bangladeshi experts and help
Bangladesh to conduct its own study on the country's gas resource.
</P>
<P>
The USGS, which has been working on assessing gas resource in
Bangladesh for the last one year, offered the training program to
have best possible local participation in the study so that it
becomes acceptable to all, the Daily Star reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The study scheduled to be completed by the end of October this
year is expected to help the Bangladeshi government take vital
decisions regarding future investment in gas sector and re-
consider whether the country should allow pipeline export of gas.
</P>
<P>
A list with names of mid level to senior officials of
Petrobangla has already been finalized and it will now be sent to
the USGS headquarters in Houston.
</P>
<P>
Leading international oil companies (IOCs), including European
oil giant Shell and U.S. oil company Unocal, have been arguing
that Bangladesh's own gas market is not expanding fast enough to
allow them to invest more in exploring oil and gas in the country.
The OICs working in Bangladesh requested the Bangladeshi
government to allow them access to a bigger gas market in India.
</P>
<P>
The demands of the OICs were being backed by the World Bank as
well as the governments of some countries including the United
States. They argued that pipeline export of gas to India would
help Bangladesh earn dollars. This earning would help Bangladesh
maintain a balance of payment as well as pay the IOCs in dollars,
as per their contracts.
</P>
<P>
But local experts resist the idea of gas export, saying that it
would be "Suicidal". They point out that the country's proven gas
reserve of 10 Trillion Cubic Feet is too inadequate to meet it's
own needs.
</P>
<P>
High level discussions between local and foreign experts
concluded that no decision on gas export could be taken before
know of gas reserve. It was unanimously agreed that first the
country must have a credible study on gas reserve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
