<HEADLINE> Myanmar Holds Seminar on Forestry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A seminar on Current International
Issues Affecting Forestry and Forest Products was opened here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar, organized by Myanmar, is attended by
officials of Myanmar National Commission for Environmental Affairs,
delegates from the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN),
representatives of FAO and ASEAN Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
There are devastating natural calamities occurring all over the
world, Myanmar Deputy Minister of Forestry Colonel Thaik Tun said
at the opening session, pointing out that these natural disasters
are in one way or the other, occurred due to environmental
degradation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that radical changes are needed, if forests all
over the world are to survive the next century. In this contrast,
solutions to forest degradation are more political than technical.
</P>
<P>
He added that in order to prevent forest from degradation,
technical solutions as well as human issues, such as the
betterment of human condition, social equity, poverty reduction,
power relations and gender roles are also needed to be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has rich resources in forestry and there is no area in
the country that can be strictly called a sandy desert.
</P>
<P>
Fifty percent of Myanmar's land area are covered with forest,
of which 18.6 percent are reserved and protected public forests,
and the country is planning to increase the area to 30 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
