<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technical Glitch Delays U.S. Anti-Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense Department said
Friday night that a technical problem had delayed for at least two
hours the third test of the National Missile Defense (NMD) system.
</P>
<P>
The glitch was with the target missile, said Defense Department
spokesman Bryan Whitman.
</P>
<P>
He said engineers were hoping to fix the problem -- related to
electronic signals inside the missile that tell ground controllers
its course of flight -- in a short time and that the test was
still expected to start at 0400 GMT.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon said earlier that a four-hour launch window opened
at 7 p.m. (0200 GMT Saturday) at Vandenberg Air Force Base where a
target missile is poised for launch.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, a U.S. "hit-to-kill" weapon would be fired atop
its own missile from Kwajalein Atoll on the Marshall Islands on
the Pacific some 6,880 kilometers away about 20 minutes after the
Vandenberg launch in an attempt to maneuver, intercept and smash
into the "enemy" warhead.
</P>
<P>
The 55-kilogram weapon, built by Raytheon Co., is designed to
hit and smash the target into space dust at a speed of 24,000 kph
in a flash that would be captured by long-range cameras.
</P>
<P>
The first such test in last October was successful, although
there was a problem with finding the approaching warhead. A second
such test failed early this year.
</P>
<P>
The results of Friday's test is expected to weigh heavily in U.
S. President Bill Clinton's planned decision in the coming months
on whether to begin building the NMD.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said earlier that he will take into account the
feasibility of such a system, its cost, its impact on the overall
national security system and an assessment of the threat to the
Untied States when he makes his decision.
</P>
<P>
The anti-missile system is designed to provide protection for
all 50 U.S. states against ballistic missile attacks. A base with
20 interceptor missiles would be built in Alaska State, along with
a new radar to help guide the missiles to their target. By 2007,
under the current schedule, the system would be expanded to 100
interceptor missiles. The Pentagon estimates the cost at 36
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Arms control experts said the NMD, opposed by the international
community, will not only spark a new arms race, but also threaten
security and stimulate nuclear proliferation, instead of promoting
security and stemming the spread of nuclear weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
