<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Rosolino Beats Hoogenband Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Italian Massimiliano Rosolino held
off strong challenge from Dutchman Pieter Van den Hoogenband to
claim his second gold medal at the European swimming championships
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rosolino captured the men's 200 meters freestyle in one minute
47.31 seconds, beating Hoogenband, six European titlist in last
year, to the runner-up by 0.31 seconds. The bronze medal went to
Paul Palmer of Britain in 1:49.54.
</P>
<P>
Hoogenband had already lost his crowns in 50 butterfly, 100
freestyle and 4x100 freestyle relay but claimed his sights fixed
on September's Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Russian-born Nina Zhivanevskaya of Spain also won her second
gold in the 100 backstroke crown to Tuesday's 200 and Hungary's
Agnes Kovacs, aiming to be a second European breaststroke treble,
won the 50 after Wednesday's 100 with the 200 still to come.
</P>
<P>
Russian diver Dmitry Sautin added the 10 meters synchronized
platform crown, won with Igor Lukashin, to his three-meter
springboard gold.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia's Martina Moravcova sprinted down the return length to
win in 58.72 seconds in the women's 100 butterfly from Poland's
Otylia Jedrzejczak, who got left on the blocks, and Sweden's
Johanna Sjoberg.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Inge de Bruijn of the Netherlands did not
defend her 100 butterfly title, preferring to concentrate on her
Olympic preparations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen-year-old Ukrainian Igor Chervynskiy, the European
short-course champion won the 1,500 meters freestyle long-course
title.  
</P>
</TEXT>
