<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Top Legal News Events in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are top legal news
events that took place in China last week.
</P>
<P>
 Macao Legislature Passes Law on Science, Technology
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council of the Macao Special Administrative
Region (SAR) has approved a law to promote the development of
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Passed by the legislature Thursday, the Law of Program for
Science and Technology stipulates that the SAR government will
establish a special fund to encourage scientific and technological
research and the application of scientific achievements.
</P>
<P>
China to Further Regulate Public Bidding Activities
</P>
<P>
China is taking further steps to regulate public bidding
activities, in a move to make sure that potential bidders obtain
relevant information equally, conveniently and accurately.
</P>
<P>
The provisional regulations for public bidding, issued on July
1 by the State Development Planning Commission (SDPC), are the
latest effort to make sure that the public bidding law, which went
into effect early this year, is fully implemented, an SDPC
official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China to Legally Standardize Language Use
</P>
<P>
China's top legislative body is preparing to enact a law on
language use nationwide.
</P>
<P>
A law draft on commonly used Chinese language was submitted
today to the 16th meeting of the Standing Committee of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC) for deliberation.
</P>
<P>
China to Revise Fisheries Law for Better Protection
</P>
<P>
China is considering revising the existing fisheries law by
introducing fishing licenses and production ceilings into the fish
stocks protection mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Agriculture Chen Yaobang, elaborated on the draft
revisions to the fisheries law to the Ninth NPC Standing Committee
at its 16th meeting, which opened Monday.
</P>
<P>
China to Amend Trust Law
</P>
<P>
The draft amendment of China's Trust Law was submitted to the
16th session of the NPC Standing Committee here Monday for
examination and approval.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, the draft was presented to the 23rd conference
of the Standing Committee of the Eighth NPC for primary
examination, and later major revisions were made to the draft.
</P>
<P>
Amendment of Customs Law Emphasizes Fight Against Smugglers
</P>
<P>
The latest draft amendment to China 's Customs Law will help
China strengthen the crack-down on smuggling-related crimes and
reinforce the protection of copyrights.
</P>
<P>
The draft was submitted to the 16th meeting of the country's
top law-making body for deliberation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
