<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Top Legal News Events in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Top Chinese legislators has urged that a study be made of the
chaotic situation of the trust companies in the country and that
the industry be brought under the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers discussed the draft law on trust business here at
the on-going meeting of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress. They criticized some local trust firms for
their irresponsible or illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
Corrupt Publisher Sentenced to Death
</P>
<P>
The Beijing No. 1 Intermediate People's Court Thursday
sentenced the former deputy director of a publishing house to
death on charges of accepting bribes worth 3.27 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Ju Jiantai, former deputy director of the Dangdai World
Publishing House, was also stripped of his political rights for
life. All of his personal property will be confiscated, according
to the court ruling.
</P>
<P>
Driver Sentenced for Damaging Tiananmen Columns
</P>
<P>
A Beijing mini-van driver was sentenced to two-and-half years
in prison for damaging some of the historic relics in front of the
Tiananmen rostrum here, Xinhua learned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Dongcheng District People's Court of Beijing tried the case
here Tuesday, and ruled that the driver's behavior constituted a
crime of carelessly damaging historic relics.
</P>
<P>
Death Sentences go to Two Men Making, Trading Fake Currencies
</P>
<P>
Cai Xiong and Xie Zhuxin, who were both found guilty of
counterfeiting currencies, were recently sentenced to death by the
Guangdong Provincial Higher People's Court.
</P>
<P>
The court also handed down a death sentence but with a two-year
probation to Chen Zongqiang, who was convicted of collaborating
with Cai in making phony currencies.
</P>
<P>
Escaped Thief Caught at Court Hearing on His Own Case
</P>
<P>
A daring thief was recently caught in a local court in the
Chinese capital, when he sat among the audience of a court hearing
on the very case he was involved, Beijing Morning News reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On June 29, the local court of Fengtai District, in southern
Beijing, held a hearing on two thieves, whose surnames were known
as Ma and Zhao. A total of three suspects, besides the caught two,
were involved in a series of stealing cases, according to the
public persecutor of the district.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Judges to Change Military-style Uniform
</P>
<P>
Judges in this national capital will shed their military-style
uniforms, characterized by epaulets and caps, and wear judicial
robes or western suits with badges starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
According to dress-code regulations, the robes are exclusively
for judges at the intermediate people's court and courts of higher
levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Top Legal News Events in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's top judge Xiao Yang and top prosecutor Han Zhubin
proposed Monday to the national legislature two separate draft
amendments to the existing 1995 laws on judges and prosecutors in
an effort to improve the quality of the country 's judiciary
personnel.
</P>
<P>
The two amendment drafts are expected to serve the purpose,
according to Xiao, president of the Supreme People's Court, and
Han, procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
Stiffer Anti-faking Measures Urged
</P>
<P>
Rampant counterfeit products are a serious menace to the
survival of enterprises and the Chinese government should deal
with the problem by enforcing legal structure.
</P>
<P>
The sales volume of counterfeit products in China has exceeded
that of smuggled goods, the English-language newspaper quoted a
senior government policy consultant as saying.
</P>
<P>
China Reviewing Trade Laws to Prepare for WTO Entry
</P>
<P>
China's law-makers are busy reviewing the country's foreign
trade laws and regulations to see if they conform to the World
Trade Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation (MOFTEC), said that all the laws, regulations and
policies concerning foreign trade and investment will be reviewed
for possible revisions and even repeal.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers Call for Tighter Supervision of Customs
</P>
<P>
Discussing a piece of legislation to give more power to the
customs to help them crack down harder on smuggling, Chinese
lawmakers also voiced concern Tuesday that their behavior should
be more closely monitored.
</P>
<P>
"Of the most serious smuggling cases uncovered so far, some
involved senior customs officers," said Tao Siju, member of the
National People's Congress Standing Committee, citing recent
notorious cases in Zhanjiang and Ningbo, two coastal cities in
south China.
</P>
<P>
Legal Assistance Hotlines Cover Almost All of China
</P>
<P>
A legal service hotline number "148" has been opened in almost
every corner of China's vast rural areas to help farmers use legal
measures to resolve disputes and protect their legitimate rights,
Minister of Justice Gao Changli said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The hotline is now available in 2,942 counties, or 96.4 percent
of China's total, and soon the entire nation will be covered, the
minister told a national teleconference on the expansion of the
hotline.
</P>
<P>
Draft Amendment Product Quality Law to Boost Consumers' Rights
</P>
<P>
The latest draft amendment to the Product Quality Law
stipulates that consumers have the right to know the facts about
the quality of products. It also specifies legal measures against
making and selling fake products.
</P>
<P>
The draft amendment was submitted to the Standing Committee of
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top
legislature, for examination and approval.
</P>
<P>
Product Quality Law to Apply to Construction Quality
</P>
<P>
Some top Chinese lawmakers proposed here Tuesday that ensuring
the quality of construction projects be an integral part of the
Product Quality Law.
</P>
<P>
In a panel deliberating the draft amendment to the law, Mao
Zhaoxi, a member of the Standing Committee of the National People'
s Congress (NPC), said that in recent years the poor quality of
some buildings and construction projects has caused great losses
to the State and the general public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
