<DOCNO> XIE20000708.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Continues in Indonesia's Ambon Despite Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Violence has continued to wreck
several areas in Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku, since the
province was placed under a state of civil emergency two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Governor Saleh Latuconsina, who is also civil emergency chief
executive in his province, said soon after the emergency took
effect, he duly took coordinated steps to quell further unrest.
</P>
<P>
"But the reality in the field was that the clashes continued,"
he was quoted by the Antara News Agency Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The latest clash took place on Thursday when residents of Liang
and Tulehu villages attacked Waai village which is only 28
kilometers from Ambon. The group renewed their assault on Friday,
destroying the remaining houses and a church with mortars, bombs
and grenades.
</P>
<P>
Data gathered from a civil emergency crisis center said that 17
Waai locals died, mostly from gunshot wounds, and 14 others were
injured. Five attackers also died in the fighting and 41 were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of buildings, including houses, schools and houses of
worship in Waai were burnt down.
</P>
<P>
Antara said that the attack had been sparked by the shooting of
three Muslims, one of them fatal, in an area located between the
warring villages two days earlier.
</P>
<P>
"If the security forces had done some early anticipation, the
clashes of the past three days would certainly not have happened,"
Latuconsina said.
</P>
<P>
About the fate of the Waai villagers, he said he had instructed
the Ambon navigation service to use a ship belonging to the
Transportation Ministry to evacuate them as well as to transport
additional security forces.
</P>
<P>
The spice islands of Maluku have been wrecked by communal
clashes since early 1999. Thousands of people were either killed
or wounded and hundreds of public buildings destroyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
