<HEADLINE> England May Mount World Club Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association of England
may turn their attention to hosting the second World club
championships after losing the right to host the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
FIFA plans to stage the championship, which Corinthians won in
January, every two years, with the next one set to take place in
the summer of 2001.
</P>
<P>
The format may change to include 12 teams, including two each
from the five continents and also the last two winners of the
Champions League.
</P>
<P>
Two sets of champions adjudged to be from the weakest of the
six continents will play off for one place while the host country
will also enter a team.
</P>
<P>
At the moment only Spain and Australia have expressed an
interest so England seem to be in a good position.
</P>
<P>
And despite losing out in the World Cup battle, FA chief
executive Adam Crozier believes England are in a better position
on the world football scene than ever before.
</P>
<P>
"I do think we are in a better position internationally than we
have been for a long time with FA chairman Geoff Thompson being
recently elected to UEFA's executive committee," he said. Before,
English football was so insular. If you are not on the inside, you
cannot influence things." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
