<HEADLINE> Iranian Security Forces Disperse Troublemakers: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran's security forces on Saturday
dispersed a group of troublemakers near the Enqelab square in
downtown Tehran, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The troublemakers clashed with the security forces at about 1730
local time (1300 GMT) and were dispersed after a few hours, the
report said, adding the windows of some buildings were broken
during the clash but nobody injured.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the troublemakers were actually divided
into two groups, one marching in support of Iran's Islamic system,
and the other voicing their support for reforms.
</P>
<P>
Saturday was a sensitive day as it was the first anniversary of
last July's student dormitory incident, which happened when anti-
riot police raided students in Tehran University to crack down on
protests against press restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The incident sparked six days of nation-wide riots, the worst
since the country's 1979 Islamic revolution. At least one person
was killed and many others injured in the riots.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the situation inside the Tehran
University was quiet on Saturday. Students held a peaceful "free-
violence meeting" to mark the incident on July 8 last year.
</P>
<P>
Students at the gathering stressed that they should avoid
violence in case they be used by conservative hardliners in the
country to undermine President Mohammad Khatami's reform programs,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
