<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Hopes David Camp Summit to Pave Way for Peace: King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
said Saturday Jordan hopes the upcoming David Camp summit by
U.S., Israeli and Palestinian leaders will help pave the way for a
just and durable peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The monarch made the remarks when meeting with visiting Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak who arrived here in the evening to brief
Jordan on Israel's stand in the three-way summit slated for July 11
in the David Camp near Washington.
</P>
<P>
King Abdullah told Barak that Jordan hopes the three parties
will do their utmost to guarantee a success of the summit to pave
the way for a peace based on international legitimacy and to meet
aspirations for peace by all peoples in the region.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also pledged his kingdom will continue its work
on a just, durable and comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 as the second
Arab country after Egypt to reach peace with the Jewish state.
Since then, Jordan has been a major peace broker between Israel and
its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Though not a party to the three-way summit, King Abdullah and
Jordanian officials have been in extensive touches with U.S.,
Israeli and Palestinian leaders and officials over the agenda of
the summit.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli and Palestinian officials remained tight lipped
to reporters over their stands in the summit.
</P>
<P>
Barak left Amman Saturday night after the brief meeting with
King Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to visit Cario to meet Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak before heading for the United States to join U.S.
President Bill Clinton and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat for the
summit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
