<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Nigerian State to Launch Sharia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's northern state of Katsina
has announced plans to introduce the controversial Islamic legal
code, the Sharia, on August 1, swelling the ranks of the states
which have adopted the law.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria Saturday quoted the Special
Assistant on Media and Publicity to the state governor, Musa
Kankaran, as saying in a statement in Katsina on Friday that the
government had submitted to the state House of Assembly a bill on
the establishment of the Sharia courts. The Sharia courts would
start adjudicating on the Sharia-related matter on August 1.
</P>
<P>
The majority muslim population in the state have been agitating
for the introduction of the Koran-based law to follow suit of
four other neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Zamfara became the first to introduce the Sharia,
though it only became effective in the state this year, followed
by Niger, Sokoto and Kano states.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian christians have objected the introduction of the
Sharia, saying the country's secularism, prescribed by the
constitution, made the introduction of the law illegal.
</P>
<P>
But Muslims countered by saying the law was a way of life and a
must for them, and that it would not affect the minority
christians living among them.
</P>
<P>
A proposal to introduce the law in Kaduna early this year led
to a violent clash between christians and muslims in the state,
with hundreds of lives lost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
