<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebel Expect EU to Contribute Funds for Social Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia (FARC) said Saturday they expect the European Union (
EU) will provide funds for social works only, instead of weapons
for the South American country.
</P>
<P>
FARC spokesman Andres Paris proposed that the EU should not
project the impression that it supports the Plan Colombia "as a
war plan promoted by the United States."
</P>
<P>
The government of President Andres Pastrana obtained in Madrid
during a meeting with donor countries, pledges for 871 million
dollars for the Plan Colombia, aimed at development, peace, and
war against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 7.5 billion dollars, of which four
billion will be contributed by the Colombian government, which
expects the remaining 3.5 billion dollars to come from the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Paris, one of the five FARC spokesmen in the National Table of
Dialogue and Negotiation with the government, said that the rebels
were very happy when the EU warned that the European contributions
would be directed to the social area.
</P>
<P>
The United States will contribute 1.3 billion dollars mainly
for military supplies for the war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
"Europe cannot become the carrot in a big stick conception as
the Plan Colombia is," said Paris.
</P>
<P>
 Some analysts said President Pastrana's controversial "Plan
Colombia" is a carrot-and-stick strategy to persuade Colombia's
estimated 22,000 rebels into cutting a peace deal after three
decades of war.
</P>
<P>
The United States will contribute 250 million dollars of the
871 million dollars in pledges received by Colombia, Spain 100
million, Norway 20 million, Japan 70 million, and the United
Nations 131 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the Inter-american Development Bank and the
Andean Corporation of Development (CAF) will grant credits for 300
million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
